article.description: Marie Ferdinand held Jackie Stiles, last season's WNBA Rookie of the Year, to nine points on 2-of-10 shooting while scoring 19 points and leading the Utah Starzz to a 69-64 victory over the Portland Fire on Thursday night.
article.headline: Ferdinand shoots Starzz past Fire
article.linkText: Double duty: Ferdinand stops Stiles, scores 19 for Starzz
article.story:
SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Shutting down Jackie Stiles got Marie Ferdinand going. Ferdinand held Stiles, last season's WNBA Rookie of the Year, to nine points on 2-of-10 shooting while scoring 19 points and leading the Utah Starzz to a 69-64 victory over the Portland Fire on Thursday night. "My defense leads to me getting into the offensive flow and we needed some big stops and some big shots down the stretch,'' Ferdinand said. Stiles was scoreless in the first half and by the time she started scoring, the Starzz had taken control of the game. "I had to let Stiles know early that it wasn't going to be easy for her tonight,'' Ferdinand said. Adrienne Goodson continued her hot start to the young season with 19 points after scoring 20 in Utah's 79-75 season-opening win over Minnesota. "I just came in from playing in Barcelona and I came in with a rhythm. I want to keep that going,'' Goodson said. Utah (2-0), playing its home opener, used a late 9-2 to take a 67-61 lead, then grabbed six offensive rebounds over the last 2:10 to hold off the Fire (0-2). "We wanted to keep them off the offensive boards, which would have put us in position to win. I think that was the biggest difference,'' Portland's Sylvia Crawley said. Crawley, who has had some of her best games facing Utah's 7-foot-2 Margo Dydek, led the Fire with 16 points despite shooting 5-of-16. Dydek scored six points, all in the first half. Ferdinand, who was 9-for-9 at the free throw line, had four points over the final 1:15. She said the way the Starzz finished "was big, I think it was huge.'' The Starzz opened the second half with a flurry of easy baskets, the kind they couldn't get to drop in the first half and took their first lead, 41-40, since early in the game. "In the second half, we did everything we wanted to do,'' Utah coach Candi Harvey said. LaQuandra Barksdale, who had 12 points, gave the Fire their last lead at 59-58 with 4:46 to play. Natalie Williams converted a follow shot and Goodson hit a leaning jumper that sparked the game-deciding run during which the Starzz overpowered the Fire on the boards. Utah outrebounded Portland 46-31 with Williams and Goodson getting 11 each.

Game notes
The Starzz finished 0-for-3 from 3-point range. Portland was 2 for-8. ... Portland led 33-28 at halftime. ... Portland shot 25 percent (8-for-32) in the second half and had six shots blocked. ... Neither team led by more than eight points.
